### 1. One-Line Summary
* Rakza Z is the spinnier, grippier, lower-geared and more deliberate hybrid-style rubber; Rakza 7 is the faster, easier, more elastic classic offensive rubber.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rakza 7 is livelier and easier to get depth with on compact strokes. Rakza Z is more muted at low impact and asks for clearer acceleration.
    * **Top End:** Rakza 7 generally reaches higher outright speed more easily, while Rakza Z trades some top-end pace for heavier rotation and a more controlled power delivery.
    * **Linearity:** Rakza Z is more linear and predictable across swing strengths. Rakza 7 has a bouncier, more catapult-driven response.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza Z is better for opening against backspin because the tackier/grippier topsheet bites the ball more securely and lifts underspin with less slip.
    * **Max Spin:** Rakza Z usually produces the heavier, nastier spin ball, especially on slow-to-medium brush contact. Rakza 7 still spins well, but its spin is more elastic than heavy.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Rakza Z has the stronger topsheet grip and more Chinese-rubber-like bite. Rakza 7 has good grip, but it is more conventionally grippy than tacky.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Rakza Z tends to produce a slightly higher, safer opening arc on spin-focused attacks. Rakza 7 is more medium throw and flatter when driven forward.
    * **Safety:** Rakza Z is generally safer on the first topspin over the table and from half-long balls. Rakza 7 is safer when you want direct pace and simpler timing in open rallies.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rakza Z feels firmer, denser, and more grab then release. Rakza 7 feels more elastic, springy, and immediately responsive.
    * **Dwell:** Rakza Z gives a more noticeable dwell sensation on brushing and spin-loaded contact. Rakza 7 has shorter-feeling dwell but easier rebound.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rakza Z is less reactive in the short game and easier to keep short on serves, pushes, and drop shots. Rakza 7 is more sensitive to incoming spin and bounce because of its livelier sponge behavior.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza Z is stronger for serve, short push, stop, and loaded receive variations. Rakza 7 is still competent, but it is not as naturally dead/contained at low impact.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rakza 7 is easier and cleaner for simple passive blocks because the rebound is more automatic and the contact is less demanding. Rakza Z can block well, but it prefers a slightly firmer hand.
    * **Active Counter:** Rakza 7 is better for quick counter-topspin exchanges and punchier timing. Rakza Z is better when you want to grab the ball, add spin, and play a more deliberate counter.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Rakza Z if:**
    * You prioritize serve, receive, opening loop, and heavy spin over pure speed.
    * You like a hybrid feeling closer to the ESN-meets-Chinese concept.
    * You want better short-game control and a more linear response.
    * You use fuller acceleration and do not rely on the rubber to create easy pace for you.

* **Choose Rakza 7 if:**
    * You want a more classic offensive rubber with easier speed and simpler point-and-shoot attacking.
    * You value rebound, countering, blocking, and all-round topspin play.
    * You prefer a more elastic feel rather than a grippy, hold-heavy contact.
    * You want something more forgiving for players coming from traditional tensor-style rubbers.
